<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06115277 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06115277 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HANDICAPPED; EQUIPMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Life is brighter these days for severely disabled youths in a state-fundedpilot program at Foothill College. A new tongue-operated device designed by aPalo Alto firm gives them control over their lives -- from turning on a VCR toshutting off the bedroom lights.;    The device lets the people, who areparalyzed from the neck down, throw away the mouth stick they use to doeveryday tasks.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Peninsula Extra  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  NEW DEVICE BIG HELP FOR QUADRIPLEGICS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Area NewsAlso ran in EX2/2, EX3/2  </MEMO><TEXT>     The device is similar to an ordinary dental retainer that fits against theroof of the mouth. It includes nine small buttons that are pushed by the tipof the tongue and uses radio frequency and infrared technology to providewireless control of a disabled person's environment.;    Called the &quot;tonguetouch keypad,&quot; it was developed by a Palo Alto firm, Zofcom Inc., and isintended to be worn 24 hours a day, giving users control of equipment not onlyfrom a wheelchair during the day but also from bed at night.;    There'sanother plus: The device is invisible when worn -- a big improvement over thebulky adaptive computer devices and other products currently available.;   Under a state Department of Education grant, Zofcom is testing the tonguetouch keypad at Foothill's disabled student computer access lab, where fourquadriplegic high school students meet twice a week to learn how to use thedevice to operate a computer and other objects, such as a television.;   Margo Dobbins, coordinator of Disabled Student Programs and Services atFoothill, said, &quot;We are excited by the new potential that this technologyoffers to students with disabilities, not only at Foothill College but for alldisabled students.&quot;;    &quot;Students can now take classes here and transfer intoa mainstream educational environment without interruption,&quot; Dobbins said.&quot;Currently, there is no method for some students to effectively make thistransfer.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DON BRIGNOLO, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910424  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  305  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday April 24, 199100115277,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>